title: MyRCCar Adjustable Steering pins, Suspension Uplinks and Servo Arm

description.text:
Here I bring you some extra parts you will need to build your rc car. They are made for MyRCCar but they could work for some bought RC Cars too.

The suspension upper link only rotates over a face so there is no need for it to be bi-articulated.

The steering pins are designed to use 4,7mm ball joint. Those are the ones i used in my OpenRC Truggy build. Maybe you can use them instead of upper arms with more ball joints. If you do this you would need about 14 ball joints.

To build MyRCCar Truggy upper links and steering pins you will have to print 4 kits of suspension upper arm and 6 ball joint pins for steering and servo arms.

You also will need some large M3 screws (more than 40mm) or M3 threaded rod to cut them from.

I recommend to introduce at less 5mm into each pin, so calculate total length with this in mind.

The parts are very small... so you won't spend many plastic if you have to re-print. I tell you this because is very important a good fit with the ball joints to make the joint strong. The actual sphere hole size is 5mm in diameter. Try some other different "horizontal expansion" to get that best fit.

title: Anet A8 slim and robust x-axis tensioner

description.text:
This x-belt tensioner combines several advantages of other designs:

  1. moves force of tension from z-axis to x-axis rods to prevent z-axis bending (similar to many others e.g. this or this)
  2. allows to reuse existing belt and pulley by placing pulley to the left of the x-axis mount (e.g. like this)
  3. doesn't increase the footprint of the printer, i.e. no parts will stick out to the right (similar to this
  4. is robust (like this)
  5. doesn't cut into x-axis width (other than e.g. this)
  6. overall minimalist design, keeping things as simple as possible, but not simpler

I generally liked lokster's solution due to compliance with design goal 3, but as some reported problems (comment 1402077 by mcorl) regarding the strength of the cap part, and this improvement conflicted with design goal 3, I moved the reinforcing parts to go inside the right hand z-axis mount. Accordingly I shortened the pulley part, which gave me the opportunity to also make it a bit lighter.

title: Build Plate Bearing Mod for TAZ 5

description.text:
In the process of building a TAZ clone, you discover how much of the original design was left to chance. That's not bashing the fine folks at Lulzbot. They've been awesome throughout the years we've used their printers. However, a simple, viable solution for one team is a nightmarish bout of tedium for another. Case in point: the linear bearings are supposed to be able to slide into these little holders with only the littlest bit of bending and squeezing. I suppose the issue is Lulzbot's bearings are nylon bushings, whereas ours are metal.
Put simply, there was no way of putting those bearings in those holders without the holder shattering. We tried every possible means of sliding, popping, pushing, or squeezing that little cylinder into that little cradle. Four broken holders later and I knew it was time for a better solution (or at least one that would work until we figure out something better).

Here is a link to the TAZ 5's source files. All I did was bring it into Tinkercad and cut out a 2mm thin section of the middle, and cloned the bottom half for the pair file. They'll still hold the bearing, but now there's a gap in the middle that lets you slide on the halves with no forcing required.

UPDATE (of sorts): Well, I've tried re-uploading these photos at least twice and somehow, something somewhere in the software pipeline needs 90-degree angles explained to it, and I lack the dry-erase board and cross-eyed sock puppet to do so. I guess I'll settle for my before and after pics looking like Art Deco-styled propaganda posters. :/

description.text:
This is a remix of Maxdarkdog's Spine dragchain. I liked the design and decided to print some links as experiment. After the print I had some suggestions and instead of asking for them to be implemented I decided that it would be easier to make them myself, print and test clearances and such.
I had to recreate the files in FreeCAD for easy editing so you also get the source as well.
The changes I added and why (from right to left):
1) chamfer at the bottom edge - no elephants foot and clean, straight contact surface
2) cut the round surface - no sharp bottom side, no overhang at the top.
3) slanted surfaces of the inside where clips reside - no bridging while printing
4 top) chamfer at the inner edge for less friction from the sharp edge
4 bottom) bottom part of the cylindrical part starts at 45deg - no overhangs
5) lip at one end of the smallest clip - easy opening
6) chamfer on inside edges of the clip - less chafing on cables

The parts are compatible and interchangeable with the original design. If you want longer clips just change the ClipV1.Pad.Sketch.Constraint35 (which is 3mm) to your desired length and export an STL.

I prinnted mine in PETG and since they bend quite a lot while assembling I am not sure if PLA will work.

E1: Added one sided clip.
E2: Added a bed connection to suit my printer. Use 2 regular clips (not one sided) to hold wires to it. Thought to make a thread in the bed hole but at the end it is held by a single ziptie through the hole. PETG holds well at 80C.

Please post your comments, makes,... :)

title: Simplified LED bridge lamp
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This is an engineers redesign of the LED Bridge lamp by Opossums. Only 5 connectors and two bridge bases are required to be printed. The remainder of the parts are sourced from your local hardware.

The bridge is scalable by increasing the length of the threaded rod sections and the height can be increased by simply increasing the length of the lower two threaded rods.

Components required (For standard 1500mm x 600mm height).

  • 6 x 5mm x 300mm threaded rods
  • 4m x 0,5mm plastic coated steel cable
  • 12 x 5mm nuts
  • 5m LED strip kit
  • 4 x 300mm x 20mm strip Correx/ aluminium
  • 1 x cable clamp

Once printed, the structure is threaded together on its side. The threaded rod will be difficult to insert. It may be useful to tap the holes first with an M5 tap. Align all the connectors and lock them in by tightening the M5 nut onto the connector. Thread the cable through the holes. Do not cut the cable - continuously thread the cable from one side of the base to the other . This will ensure that the tension on both sides of the bridge are equilized.

Tension the cable sufficiently to ensure that the bases are parallel. Lock the cable tension with the cable clamp.

The bridge can now be lifted into an upright position.

The LED strip needs to be cut and mounted on the 20mm wide Correx or Aluminium. The amount of LEDs required are dependent on the LED wattage. A dimmer is essential for different light or mood requirements.

description.text:
This is a Dial Gauge adapter for TEVO Tornado, but openscad file is provided with parametric variables so can be adapted to CR10, Anet.. or any other squared hotend printer, or different dial gauge screw size.

The aim is to measure the heatbed level easily by reading the dial in several X,Y positions. The result is much accurate than the piece of paper, a dial gauge are very cheap in ebay, etc.

The idea comes from https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2796961, but after printing it, it did not fit TEVO hotend screws and only is attached by a weak flap pressure so it moves and fall easily. Furthermore, due its shape, it was very difficult to print without supports

This new design use the hotend fan screws and the gauge original screw pad, so provide a very solid attachment, essential for accurate level reading.

You can either dismount a single gauge screw (leaving the adapter on the hotend), or even leave the dial (it is not heavy), but keep the bar up with an accessory. I recommend to dismount it,so you can print fast as before.

It prints better vertically (see picture) and in very short time.

Have Fun!

Many Acura NSXs don't have cupholders, and aftermarket options require screw holes or work very poorly. Acura's own "pop up" cupholders are pretty crummy too. This retrofit utilizes the interior cavity of the center arm rest and fits snugly inside the pocket to keep a drink in place without the need to add any screws for anchoring. It is also out of the way of the passenger foot well!

Roughly based on a common style of bench in New York City's Central Park. There are two leg widths, and two bench widths in this set. The bench slat widths are 100mm and 170mm, allowing for a wide or compact bench. The legs are provided in 4mm width and 7mm width.

Scaling

If you take a standard Central Park bench height as 80cm, or 800mm, tall, a 12:1 scaling would give you a miniature bench 66.7mm tall - this would mean printing at approximately 70% of this model scale.

Printing

All of the pieces are provided as individual STLs. You will need to print:

  • 2 legs
  • 7 slats

The two legs can easily be printed together, even in a small print volume, by rotating one leg 180° and nesting the legs close together.

I've tested the print with the legs sliced with 0.06mm layers and slats sliced with 0.20mm layers.

Assembly

Depending on your layer size when slicing, the slats will fit more or less snug to the legs. A small bit of glue between each leg and slat should be sufficient. Getting everything aligned and glued takes a bit of trial-and-error, but I recommend attaching two or three bench (not back) slats to one leg, and letting them dry for a few minutes. Once those slats are dried, attach them to the other leg to stabilize and balance the whole miniature. Then procede slat by slat to complete the model.

title: Bowden tube support clamp for Tevo Tarantula

description.text:
Bowden tube support clamp for the original Tarantula carriage. In some circumstances (high Z or short tube), the bowden tube tends to overflex just before the hotend. This clip snaps directly on the original carriage, providing a more tapered bend for the tube into the hotend. Easy to print and designed to fit just behind the radial fan fang (as pictured). Supports the tube in any direction.

Comes in two variants:

v1: more rigid, longer vertical support shaft. Use this if you bundle all cables to the bowden tube itself.
v2: taller, wider support shaft. Sufficient for the bowden tube only.

Instructions:

1) decide if you need this (you know you do)
2) print flat, no brim, 10% infill max at 0.15mm layer height
3) remove the filament, disconnect the PTFE tube from the feed stepper
4) slide the clip in (should slide smoothly)
5) push firmly (holding the carriage) until it clicks in place
6) reconnect tube, reinsert filament
7) resume printing

title: Spriya Split Duct - Modified (Downward Airflow) for ANET A8

description.text:
A modified version of the Spriya split fan duct (originally created by lokster, published Feb 24, 2017). Modified in response to a couple complaints about the original model cooling the extruder too much (~4°C). The STL file was simply modified on vertary.com to squash the exhaust n ~half, and pushing the upper portion forward a bit, in an attempt to force the flow of air more downward / not directly at the extruder. This will probably also result in a higher velocity of exhaust. As this was a modified/edited STL format that was again exported as an STL - the quality may be poor. Please note that I do not currently have access to this printer and have not tested this model for fitment or even printability. If anyone shows interest in this modification I will spend some time modeling a better version in a proper program. Please leave feedback as to whether or not yo would like me to do so. Also note that, as I plan to purchase an A8 printer, an updated version of this is sure to come along at some point.
Additionally, on lokster's original post, he gives information about how to self adjust the extruder temperature through G-code. So, this model is simply for people that don't have that option for whatever reason.

Imported the original STL (non "thickwall" version) into vectary.com, which is a web-based 3D modeling website. Simply used the line select tool to move the upper portion of the exhaust downward and "forward". The modified model was then exported back to an STL file.

"C:\Program Files\OpenSCAD\openscad.exe" "$(FULL_CURRENT_PATH)"

I cannot stand the scenario tokens that come with the game and have a hard time telling the a/b/d/e/g tokens apart. When you're looking at the board from different perspectives or digging for the right tokens during setup you might ask yourself: WHY DID THEY PICK THIS FONT?! Love the game but, dang.

FWP needs FW solution! This design, though not particularly thematic, should solve this issue of legibility with an added bonus that 3D printed standee holders sit nicely on top of them as opposed to the small original tokens.

Files:
GloomSolidMarkers_004.stl - This version has a solid background.
GloomSolidTest_002.stl - A single solid marker to test slicer settings.
GloomHexPatternMarkers_002.stl - This version has a honeycomb background pattern.

GloomHexRoundMarkers_001.stl - This is a round version with honeycomb background pattern.
GloomHexRoundTest_001.stl - A single round/honeycomb marker to test slicer settings.

I pause the print at .75mm to change filament (layer 5, please check single layer view in your slicer and/or print one of the test files to make sure it's right before printing all of them) from black PLA to white PLA since that's all I have. Red/white or red/gray would be more in line with the original tokens.

I have added a 5mm x 5mm square in order to get the extruder primed as I was running into an issue where I wasn't getting full extrusion of the new filament until partway into the first token. YMMV.

*Thank you to DasGooch44 on Reddit for pointing out that the original solid design blocks obstacles that the tokens are often placed on. The honeycomb pattern markers will show some of the board (or doors/obstacles/etc) through the marker.

Designed in Tinkercad. I really need to learn a piece of real software :/

description.text:
The basic plastic printerbot frequently produces bands on the sides of the prints which match the z-threaded rod pitch. This is most obvious on prints using .2mm or thinner slices.
In order to find the source of the problem I made custom parts to lock the bearings and rods in place. I also made an external bracing.
The source of the banding appears to be a rocking in the z-motors.
This causes uneven z-lift which in turn causes some layers to be squashed and buldge on the sides.
This is easiely fixed with a few wedges but the other parts may be of some use for people wanting a more rigid bot or to re-purpose for something else. Also the z-motors are .5mm too far out on my bot. This is an error in the orginal CAD files.
I have a corrected but untest version here. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:26542
I will be publishing more modified parts when I find time.
I have done the CAD for a modified base with extra motor support but this is overkill for most people.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:28557

Wedges.
You can print these wedges if you like but you might want to make them out of something else - I used clothes-peg parts originaly. The frame.
As stated earlier - you probably don't need this frame to get good prints. My bot lives in a bamboo serving tray so my bottom bracket is designed to mate with the corners of the tray. It could be modified to work with a sheet of ply or something else.
I use the same sort of 5/16 threaded rod as is used in the PB kit.
The smooth rod joiner and the V joiner at at the top mate using a tapered fitting. It was intended that the two nut-knobs could be unscrewed without changing the other adjustments and the bot could easily be removed. Mines are too tight to come apart easily and some sanding is needed. It is possible my taper is too shallow.
(PS it is sort of working). I have longer z-smooth rods but I'm not using the extra travel ATM. I may have to modify the design to get full height as the e-motor may (or may not) conflict.
If I want full height and width I will need to increase the length of the top joiner rod and remove the front part of the spool holder A-frame.

description.text:
Yet another GoPro Session mount

But...

  • Easy printable without support mess. No ugly overhangs.
  • 20, 25, 30, 35, 40, 45 and 60 degree angles
  • Locked "double wall" for stiffness
  • Unlocked for a bit better shock protection
  • Rear and top button access holes
  • Camera shaped cavity
  • Easy rip or cut off Integrated front hole support as an option
  • Suitable for many mounting styles
  • Superview compatible (didn't test it yet myself, confirmed by a friend)

This is a lite mount, not supposed to protect Session from hard impacts. Maybe later I'll design something beefy with bumpers.

Locked and unlocked versions

Unlocked, springy, version is for a bit better shock resistance.

Locked, stiff, version is to minimise vibrations in hard racing.

Integrated support

As this mount is designed for easy printing without supports, but with one exception, the front hole. It is quite big to print without support. That why I've added simple support, that is easy to remove by ripping or cutting off.
There is two option of the files with or without front hole integrated support. If you prefer to do own supports, chose the files without support.

Mount options

Zip or cable ties can be inserted directionally or sideway.

Mount can be also bolted to the frame using a printable inserts. M3 bolt holes are in 15x20mm pattern.

Cavity

There is Session shaped cavity on bottom and top part of the mount to keep camera in place and prevent slipping off.

This model works with PLA and ABS on my Tevo Tarantula.

Best results if no brim is used. (There is a little brim between the 2 bores in the bottom part included in the model. It prevents some warping tendencies I observed in that area. Remove after printing so that the M8 bolt can be inserted.)

You might use supports to improve the bridging in the centre of the bottom part. But the results were not too bad without supports in my case.

Assembly:
For PLA the conical sections of top and bottom made a tight and permanent fit without any glue in my case. (Print bottom part first and press top part on it directly after taking it from the heated bed.)
For ABS I wetted the joint with acetone before fitting to make a permanent connection.
Diameters of small holes often turn out to be smaller than intended on my printer. Widen these holes with a drill if necessary for your application.

Use:
I hope the photos eliminate any ambiguities about the intended use:
• inner hole in sidewall of spool to fix start of cable
• multiple holes on the outer diameter of the sidewalls to fix end of cable
• 3.6 mm bores around the centre to take up skewers (or M3 rods) as handles for manual spooling operation. (This will help me to stow away e.g. towrope on the RC flying field.)
• Center bore to insert and latch M8 bolt for fixing spool in chuck of cordless screwdriver.
Designcad for modelling, Cura for slicing.

Personal comment

The motivation for this project was to have a more substantial replacement for weak cable spools that had become broken over the years (you can see one of them on the photos).
For towing of my RC model planes I needed proper spools to store towing ropes etc. To meet such requirements the design is not the lightest and will consume about 30g of ABS or 34 g of PLA.

title: Slant 3D Reusable Filament Spool
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
We run a commercial 3D printing farm. We have literally thrown away hundreds of spools and we hate it. The weight of the spools increases our freight cost, and they are just a waste of plastic in general, not to mention the environment issues. So we created this reusable filament spool as a resource to filament manufacturers that wish to eliminate the cost of spools to their customers and in their production.

We recently ran across the MasterSpool, by RichRep and while he had a good concept for individual 3D printers, the MasterSpool doesn't work at the larger scale. It uses too much material and has more Guff associated with it than what we want. So we continued on and designed a spool that we wanted to use in our printer farm.

The SlantSpool is just one piece, printed twice. We created a special latching system, so there is no right and left. You can put any two of the SlantSpool halves together. This is great when you have a lot of them because you don't have to worry about printing a right and left, which saves some mental effort, and if you ever break one, all you have to do is grab a half that isn't being used. There is only one spare part you need.

We operate a 3D printing farm that competes with injection molding. We are working with filament suppliers to manufacture these rolls at scale now. In order to make that production affordable at scale we had to reduce the material used. The MasterSpool is too beefy to be manufactured at scale with 3D printing.

So we went ahead and reduced the material needed by half. We made the outer walls thinner and used ribs along the inside of the walls to give it the necessary rigidity. Then we changed the securing mechanism of the Spool to a design that decreased the surface area of the spool so that it prints more quickly and uses less material to create the walls.

The connecting system is actually the true innovation in the SlantSpool. We have made a quarter-turn system that is fast and easy to put together. You just press the two halves together, twist and it is latched. This is much faster than spinning the halves several times to get them to stick together.

The SlantSpool was designed for the either the frugal Maker or the commercial user. Anyone that would like to have many of these manufactured for their filament refills may contact us at [email protected]

title: Hinged Chest with Working Lock and Wood Texture

description.text:
My godson has some kind of obsession with collecting small things in small chests, and he wanted a chest with a working lock. So, for his next birthday I took athey's Small Hinged Treasure Chest and designed a lock mechanism for it. Of course it is the most basic lock possible with only one possible key, and picking it is trivial, but it is functional.
I also spiffed up the overall looks of the chest with extra details, like the excellent wood texture from the OpenForge Wooden Floors by devonjones.
The hinge has been made slightly beefier to reduce the risk of it breaking.

To unlock the chest, rotate the key counter-clockwise and open the lid while keeping the key turned. The lock cannot be left in the open position, closing the chest automatically locks it. This video demonstrates how the chest works.

I made three different key designs, although the skull key will probably be the most popular with little (and big) children by far :)

Assembly is rather straightforward, but the parts must be printed and mounted accurately for the lock to neither fail to close, nor be sloppy. See the images for instructions. On a well-calibrated printer, the parts should only require minimal post-processing to make them fit. If your prints tend to be sloppy, some extra sanding and scraping may be required. See the post-printing section for more details.

The dimensions are 76 × 46 × 57 mm for the bulk of the chest, and 76 × 51 × 58 mm with the hinges and details included. It should be possible to scale up the model, but you may need to scale up the latches a tiny bit more in two of the three dimensions to keep them a tight fit.

Notes:

Supports should not be needed. Even though the dome of the lid has overhangs that go beyond 45°, those overhangs are actually printed as bridges, therefore if your printer passes the bridge torture test, you do not need supports.

The chest and lid were printed with 0.2 mm layers in rigid.ink ‘Pearl Red’ ABS. I used a brim to avoid warping.
The latches and keys were printed with 0.1 mm layers and 3 perimeters. It is important to print these parts with thin layers, to ensure they have an accurate thickness. You should also print them slowly to ensure the latches have an accurate shape.

If you print this with a rather flexible filament like PETG, the lower latch may be too flexible, and you may need to print it in PLA or ABS instead for it to be stiff enough.

Make sure to remove any traces of a ‘squashed’ first layer (elephant's foot syndrome) on the latches and hole in the lid, through sanding or scraping with a knife. Try hooking the latches into each other with your hands: they shouldn't easily slip out of each other. If they get unhooked easily, try to adjust the hook shape with a knife.

The lower latch (long piece) must be mounted in the chest with the hook pointing to the right, and the top perfectly flush with the edge (simply pushing it in on a flat table should do the trick). If you cannot push it deep enough, scrape off some material from the bottom end.
The latch in the lid must have its hook pointing to the left, and ideally the edges of the square part should be flush with the bottom edge of the lid. If the lock doesn't catch, you either need to pull this latch out again by a fraction of a millimeter, or shave off a bit of material with an X-acto knife.

If the lid doesn't close easily due to the latch bumping against the top edge of the chest, try sanding or scraping a bit of material from the front edge of the latch.

When printed accurately, the parts should fit tightly enough that no glue is required. The advantage of not using glue, is that the latches will pop out of their sockets if the chest is pulled open with excessive force, instead of breaking and leaving bits behind that are impossible to repair. In other words, you need to make a choice between a chest that is harder to open without a key, but will be broken if someone does manage to open it; or a chest that is easier to open but can be repaired if needed. After all, this is just a toy, not a secure storage device!

If you do want to use glue, do not use cyanoacrylate (super glue) unless you are skilled in using it. It tends to solidify in a fraction of a second, causing the parts to become stuck before they can be inserted deep enough, making the lock unusable.

I don't recommend trying to print the lid with the open end up. The result will likely be ugly unless you're using soluble support material. Moreover, you would need about as much support material as when printing flat side down anyway.
You should be able to print this flat side down without supports, even though the top of the dome violates the typical 45° rule and every automatic overhang detection will try to convince you that you need supports. Supports are not needed because the contours are anchored at both sides, which means they are actually bridges. Therefore if you have passed the bridge torture test, you should be able to print this without any supports, like I did. A cooling fan will help a lot to print these bridges/overhangs correctly. I only saw some minor curling up of the middle of those bridged contours in the very last layers before the top of the dome was sealed, but it was not problematic at all.
If you're in doubt whether you can print this without supports, you can slice the upper section of the lid in a mesh editor of your choice, and print that part.

description.text:
Marlin 1.1.8 firmware for the Anycubic Kossel(mini & plus) Delta Printer.
It is modified for delta auto calibration, auto fan control, Neopixel LED strip, TMC2100(TMC2130 stand-alone mode), piezo z-probe sensor.
You need to install Adafruit Neopixel library.
I have set vref on TMC2130 to 1v.
Use at your own risk.

Delta Auto Calibration Steps

Clean the nozzle and install the sensor.
Run pronterface and send the commands.

  1. M119 (check sensor status)
    execute M119 while pressing the sensor.
    If everything is set up correctly, you will see 'z_min: TRIGGERED' message
  2. M502 (factory reset)
  3. M500 (store settings)
  4. M503 (get current settings)
  5. G33 (auto calibration)
    more accurate calibration: G33 P1 > G33 P2 > G33 P5 > G33 P10
  6. G33 P1(set height)
  7. calibrate the z-offset
    remove the sensor. Then do the paper test and obtain the z-offset.
    g1 z20, g1 z0, g1 z-0.01 ......
    set new z-offset: M851 Zxx.xx (old z-offset + z-offset)
    set new height: M665 Hxxx.xx (old height - z-offset)
  8. M500 (store settings)
  9. print the calibration circle and adjust the height again
    change endstop offset: M666 Xxx.xx Yxx.xx Zxx.xx

I disabled G29(auto bed leveling) because it make things worse.

title: Yet Another Kossel XL Bed Support

description.text:
This is a bed support for Kossel XL printer, designed around an Onyx 310mm bed heater with twelve M3 screw holes and 360mm 2020 horizontal extrusions. I provide OpenSCAD source files so you can tweak the design if desired or necessary; but beyond a certain point it may be better to simply find another bed support.

To be useful, you'll need to print three of these Things. Each requires four M5x16 screws and four T-nuts for attaching the support to the frame, plus one to three M3x12 or M3x16 screws (depending on how thick your bed is) and nuts for mounting the bed, and matched M3 wing nuts or regular nuts with printed bits to hold the bed down. If you like, you can add springs and washers to enable physical bed leveling.

The spacing is very tight around the bed screws. During assembly, it helps to not fully tighten the bed support to the frame until after you've fitted the bed. Although the geometry provides very little "wiggle room," there's enough when the support is not fully screwed down to enable some fine-tuning of position. You may also need to straighten some of the bed screws; they don't always go in quite straight. I used two screws per vertex, for half the Onyx's twelve screws. Using three per vertex would probably make it too difficult to fit everything in place. One per vertex may well be adequate.

This Thing is designed to be used with the Kossel Mini 2020 Frame Brace (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1686378), but can be used without it.

title: TinyG V8 Box with 90mm fan mount

description.text:
I made this because I plan to run a CNC rounter and needed something that held the board in place, that had a fan mount, and dust cover. So I decided to make this.

This has inserts for 4MM machine nuts to hold the fan in place. As well as it uses motherboard standoffs that you can screw in by hand to secure the TinyG Board.

There could be some tight/loose tolerances due to just the 3D printing process itself, I've had a couple tight then loose fits without changing anything.

This is the first thing I've modeled for public use, so hopefully it all goes well.

Hardware Needed

optional if you are using a fan

  • 4x 4MM Hex Nut
  • 4x 4MM X 30MM screw
  • 90mm fan
  • dust cover (I just used a speaker screen as mine)

non-optional

  • 4x Motherboard standoffs as well as screws to go into the standoffs
